<Layouts.flash_group flash={@flash} />
<section class="ck-shell ck-shell-tight">
  <div class="ck-section-header">
    <div>
      <p class="ck-kicker">Getting started</p>
      <h1 class="ck-section-title">Go from install to first finding in five minutes</h1>
      <p class="ck-lead ck-lead-tight">
        ControlKeel is the control tower that turns agent-generated work into secure, scoped, validated, production-ready delivery. ControlKeel turns agent output into production engineering. Start it, attach a project, and enter the proof console loop quickly.
      </p>
      <p class="ck-note">
        Agent output is cheap. Reviewability, security, release safety, and cost control are not. ControlKeel exists to govern that layer from the first attach.
      </p>
      <p class="ck-note">
        It also works as a rescue path when another generator already touched the repo: bootstrap the governed project, expose the production boundary, and use findings, proofs, and proxy flows to recover safely.
      </p>
    </div>
    <a href={~p"/"} class="ck-link">Back home</a>
  </div>

  <div class="ck-grid ck-grid-dashboard">
    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Packaged binary</p>
      <ol class="ck-mini-list">
        <li>Run `controlkeel` to boot the local web app.</li>
        <li>In your target project, run `controlkeel attach opencode`.</li>
        <li>ControlKeel auto-bootstraps the governed binding on first use.</li>
        <li>
          Use `controlkeel bootstrap` or `controlkeel init` only if you want to do it explicitly.
        </li>
        <li>Ask OpenCode to add a hardcoded secret or unsafe SQL query.</li>
        <li>Open mission control or run `controlkeel findings` to verify the block.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Source setup</p>
      <ol class="ck-mini-list">
        <li>Run `mix setup` once.</li>
        <li>Run `mix phx.server` in the ControlKeel repo.</li>
        <li>
          In your target project, run `mix ck.attach opencode` from the same installed source environment.
        </li>
        <li>`mix ck.init` remains available when you want an explicit setup step.</li>
        <li>Use the demo snippet from `docs/demo-script.md` to trigger the first finding.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">What it is not</p>
      <ul class="ck-mini-list">
        <li>Not another IDE or coding model</li>
        <li>Not a prompt marketplace</li>
        <li>Not post-hoc review only</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Occupation-first onboarding</p>
      <p class="ck-note">
        Start from what best describes your work. ControlKeel picks the domain pack, interview language, and governance posture behind the scenes instead of asking non-experts to choose a framework first.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Project rescue</p>
      <p class="ck-note">
        If another tool already made changes, bootstrap the repo, use `controlkeel watch`, findings, proofs, and `ck_validate`, then add governed proxy only when the tool can point at compatible OpenAI or Anthropic endpoints.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Other supported agents</p>
      <ul class="ck-mini-list">
        <li>
          `controlkeel attach codex-cli` installs native Codex skills and the CK operator agent.
        </li>
        <li>
          `controlkeel attach vscode` and `controlkeel attach copilot` prepare repo-native skills plus MCP config.
        </li>
        <li>
          OpenCode is the recommended MCP-plus-instructions quick start; Cursor, Windsurf, Kiro, Amp, Gemini CLI, Continue, and Aider use the same portable bundle path.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <a href={~p"/skills"} class="ck-link">Open skills studio</a>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Proof console loop</p>
      <ul class="ck-mini-list">
        <li>Mission Control for active task state, risk, and approvals</li>
        <li>Proof Browser for immutable evidence and rollback guidance</li>
        <li>Ship Dashboard and benchmarks for outcome evidence</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Governed delivery lifecycle</p>
      <ul class="ck-mini-list">
        <li>Intent intake and execution brief compilation at `/start`.</li>
        <li>Task graph, validation, and findings during governed execution.</li>
        <li>Proof bundles, Ship Dashboard, and benchmarks as stewardship evidence.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Autonomy and findings</p>
      <p class="ck-note">
        Severity maps to expected human gates, and findings stay readable in plain language. LLM advisory is optional and needs a provider. See
        <code class="font-mono text-sm">docs/autonomy-and-findings.md</code>
        in the repository.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="ck-card">
      <p class="ck-mini-label">Operating modes</p>
      <ul class="ck-mini-list">
        <li>
          Local packaged mode is fully shipped and useful with SQLite, Ollama, or heuristic fallback.
        </li>
        <li>
          Cloud and headless operation exist partially today through runtime exports, webhooks, and service-account paths.
        </li>
        <li>Broader team and enterprise platform work remains a later branch.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
